WEBVTT

1
00:00:09.244 --> 00:00:10.463
﻿- About 15 years ago,

2
00:00:10.463 --> 00:00:12.397
I watched the film Life After Life,

3
00:00:12.397 --> 00:00:14.098
which became part of my all-time

4
00:00:14.098 --> 00:00:16.601
must-see list of impactful videos.

5
00:00:16.601 --> 00:00:19.153
The subject was near-death experiences,

6
00:00:19.153 --> 00:00:20.772
featuring Dr. Raymond Moody.

7
00:00:20.772 --> 00:00:22.607
Raymond, as he prefers to be called,

8
00:00:22.607 --> 00:00:24.258
is referred to as the father

9
00:00:24.258 --> 00:00:25.710
of near-death experiences.

10
00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.446
But, he will, and did, quickly correct anyone

11
00:00:28.446 --> 00:00:30.348
who proffers this title upon him,

12
00:00:30.348 --> 00:00:32.284
and saying that Plato is, in truth,

13
00:00:32.284 --> 00:00:34.519
the father of near-death experiences.

14
00:00:34.519 --> 00:00:36.164
His life is a paradox,

15
00:00:36.164 --> 00:00:37.822
in that he's devoted 50 years

16
00:00:37.822 --> 00:00:39.658
to understanding and documenting

17
00:00:39.658 --> 00:00:41.792
a phenomenon that is often referred to

18
00:00:41.792 --> 00:00:43.695
as a spiritual experience,

19
00:00:43.695 --> 00:00:46.898
while maintaining that NDEs can also be explained

20
00:00:46.898 --> 00:00:49.551
through pure logic.

21
00:00:49.968 --> 00:00:54.968
Raymond, you have such an iconic kind of background

22
00:00:55.139 --> 00:00:57.175
in the subject of near-death experience,

23
00:00:57.175 --> 00:00:59.344
and I know that you don't really view it that way,

24
00:00:59.344 --> 00:01:01.012
per se, but that's the fact.

25
00:01:01.012 --> 00:01:04.883
I mean, the original film, Life After Life,

26
00:01:04.883 --> 00:01:07.002
through the last couple of decades is,

27
00:01:07.002 --> 00:01:08.990
I have given that to people

28
00:01:08.990 --> 00:01:11.108
that are approaching the end,

29
00:01:11.108 --> 00:01:12.724
with such pleasure,

30
00:01:12.724 --> 00:01:15.059
because of the joy that it brings people,

31
00:01:15.059 --> 00:01:17.862
to see that this experience is truly

32
00:01:17.862 --> 00:01:20.532
the passageway back to the true self.

33
00:01:20.532 --> 00:01:23.101
And, on that note,

34
00:01:23.101 --> 00:01:25.471
I heard you say, in your lecture last night,

35
00:01:25.471 --> 00:01:26.972
you've never been a religious person,

36
00:01:26.972 --> 00:01:28.923
and you were raised in the south.

37
00:01:28.923 --> 00:01:29.837
<v ->Yeah.
<v Regina>I assume</v>

38
00:01:29.837 --> 00:01:31.018
it was kind of bible-belt country?

39
00:01:31.018 --> 00:01:35.114
<v ->My dad was a military officer, a surgeon,</v>

40
00:01:35.114 --> 00:01:39.934
and served in World War Two, in the Pacific theater,

41
00:01:39.934 --> 00:01:40.952
as a medic.

42
00:01:40.952 --> 00:01:44.289
And, he went away to World War Two,

43
00:01:44.289 --> 00:01:45.724
on the day I was born,

44
00:01:45.724 --> 00:01:48.176
and didn't come back 'til I was 18 months old.

45
00:01:48.176 --> 00:01:49.009
<v Regina>Oh.</v>

46
00:01:49.009 --> 00:01:51.930
<v ->And, that generation didn't talk.</v>

47
00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:53.999
But, you know, as you grow older,

48
00:01:53.999 --> 00:01:57.409
you realize what trauma they went through.

49
00:01:59.209 --> 00:02:01.306
So, later in life, I've finally come to realize

50
00:02:01.306 --> 00:02:04.809
Dad must have had some horrific experiences.

51
00:02:06.869 --> 00:02:09.113
The way I put it together, it sort of embittered him.

52
00:02:09.113 --> 00:02:12.410
Religion to him was a non-starter.

53
00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:14.025
So,that was good, from him.
<v Regina>He'd seen</v>

54
00:02:14.025 --> 00:02:15.220
too many atrocities?

55
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:19.290
<v ->Yeah, and that benefited me,</v>

56
00:02:19.290 --> 00:02:23.528
in that I didn't go through all that church stuff.

57
00:02:23.528 --> 00:02:27.948
And so, I mean, I'm not religious,

58
00:02:27.948 --> 00:02:30.472
but, it's not a crusade of mine, I just--

59
00:02:30.472 --> 00:02:31.542
<v Regina>Right, but, the thing</v>

60
00:02:31.542 --> 00:02:32.980
that's interesting is--
<v ->I have no interest</v>

61
00:02:32.980 --> 00:02:34.191
in it.
<v Regina>is, so many people</v>

62
00:02:34.191 --> 00:02:36.127
that go through this experience,

63
00:02:36.127 --> 00:02:38.176
they always refer to it as a spiritual experience.

64
00:02:38.176 --> 00:02:40.010
But, some people cross the line,

65
00:02:40.010 --> 00:02:42.380
and really start applying almost the term

66
00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:45.116
religious experience, in the place of spiritual.

67
00:02:45.116 --> 00:02:46.785
You know, I have to wonder,

68
00:02:46.785 --> 00:02:48.754
nothing happens by accident.

69
00:02:48.754 --> 00:02:51.190
You've been doing this incredible work,

70
00:02:51.190 --> 00:02:55.527
as a deep academic, in this area.

71
00:02:55.527 --> 00:02:57.461
But, you were drawn to it, obviously,

72
00:02:57.461 --> 00:02:58.363
for other reasons.

73
00:02:58.363 --> 00:03:00.732
There's a deeply spiritual component,

74
00:03:00.732 --> 00:03:03.001
to being drawn so deeply into this work

75
00:03:03.001 --> 00:03:04.152
that helps people so much.

76
00:03:04.152 --> 00:03:05.204
<v ->Well, by definition.</v>

77
00:03:05.204 --> 00:03:10.204
However, you could equally use that word philosophical.

78
00:03:10.475 --> 00:03:11.639
I went to--
<v Regina>Yes.</v>

79
00:03:11.639 --> 00:03:12.729
<v ->the University of Virginia,</v>

80
00:03:12.729 --> 00:03:15.680
at the age of 18, in 1962,

81
00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:18.716
planning to be an astronomy major,

82
00:03:18.716 --> 00:03:20.818
and getting my PhD in astronomy.

83
00:03:20.818 --> 00:03:23.588
But, I'd also been interested in philosophy,

84
00:03:23.588 --> 00:03:28.459
in high school, so when I went to UVA,

85
00:03:28.459 --> 00:03:30.761
in my first year, I took a philosophy course,

86
00:03:30.761 --> 00:03:34.298
and immediately decided that's what I wanted to do.

87
00:03:34.298 --> 00:03:37.201
And the specific thing that brought me into it

88
00:03:37.201 --> 00:03:38.737
was Plato.

89
00:03:38.737 --> 00:03:40.971
And, Plato was the first person

90
00:03:40.971 --> 00:03:43.841
I had ever encountered, at age 18,

91
00:03:43.841 --> 00:03:48.841
who even discussed this notion of an afterlife.

92
00:03:48.963 --> 00:03:51.415
And, the fact that he took it seriously

93
00:03:51.415 --> 00:03:53.117
indicated to me that it was something

94
00:03:53.117 --> 00:03:54.954
you should pay attention to.

95
00:03:54.954 --> 00:03:57.488
So, at the end of Plato's Republic,

96
00:03:57.488 --> 00:04:00.358
which I read at my first semester at UVA,

97
00:04:00.358 --> 00:04:02.527
there's this near-death experience,

98
00:04:02.527 --> 00:04:05.096
and that's what perked my interest.

99
00:04:05.096 --> 00:04:06.665
And then, three years later,

100
00:04:06.665 --> 00:04:09.567
while I was still an undergraduate philosophy student,

101
00:04:09.567 --> 00:04:13.805
in 1965, I met a wonderful man,

102
00:04:13.805 --> 00:04:16.590
who was a professor of psychiatry there,

103
00:04:16.590 --> 00:04:19.978
Dr. George Ritchie, one of my philosophy professors,

104
00:04:19.978 --> 00:04:20.846
told me about him,

105
00:04:20.846 --> 00:04:23.314
and he, some years before,

106
00:04:23.314 --> 00:04:26.076
he had been pronounced dead, twice,

107
00:04:26.076 --> 00:04:27.819
within a 9-minute period,

108
00:04:27.819 --> 00:04:30.789
and in the interim, had the first of these

109
00:04:30.789 --> 00:04:33.024
near-death experiences I ever heard.

110
00:04:33.024 --> 00:04:35.126
So, to make a long story short,

111
00:04:35.126 --> 00:04:36.595
started investigating it,

112
00:04:36.595 --> 00:04:41.595
got my PhD in philosophy in 1969,

113
00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:45.169
and then, became a philosophy professor,

114
00:04:45.169 --> 00:04:47.171
and immediately started hearing these

115
00:04:47.171 --> 00:04:49.274
from my students.

116
00:04:49.274 --> 00:04:52.777
So, it's a long process, but that's how it started.

117
00:04:52.777 --> 00:04:54.079
<v Regina>So, over this process,</v>

118
00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:57.315
where was your first personal experience,

119
00:04:57.315 --> 00:04:59.918
with someone, up close and personal,

120
00:04:59.918 --> 00:05:02.386
that had gone through a near-death experience.

121
00:05:02.386 --> 00:05:05.572
What point in this journey and education?

122
00:05:05.572 --> 00:05:06.508
<v ->1965.</v>

123
00:05:06.508 --> 00:05:07.208
<v Regina>Okay.</v>

124
00:05:07.208 --> 00:05:08.592
One of my philosophy professors

125
00:05:08.592 --> 00:05:11.997
told me that, right there in Charlottesville,

126
00:05:11.997 --> 00:05:13.130
was Dr. Ritchie.

127
00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:14.999
He’s a very well-known person,

128
00:05:14.999 --> 00:05:17.368
in Charlottesville,

129
00:05:17.368 --> 00:05:21.138
and very receptive to talking to student groups,

130
00:05:21.138 --> 00:05:25.029
so in 1965, I heard Dr. Ritchie talk.

131
00:05:25.029 --> 00:05:26.587
<v Regina>So, that was your first exposure,</v>

132
00:05:26.587 --> 00:05:27.328
was his experience, or?

133
00:05:27.779 --> 00:05:29.591
<v ->Well, if you don’t count Plato,</v>

134
00:05:29.591 --> 00:05:30.992
<v Regina>Well, yes.</v>
<v ->three years before.</v>

135
00:05:30.992 --> 00:05:32.058
<v ->Yeah, but, what I realized,</v>

136
00:05:32.058 --> 00:05:34.453
from Dr. Ritchie’s experience,

137
00:05:34.453 --> 00:05:36.187
was that it was not just something

138
00:05:36.187 --> 00:05:38.356
pertaining to ancient Greece.

139
00:05:38.356 --> 00:05:39.624
<v Regina>Yes, and then,</v>

140
00:05:39.624 --> 00:05:42.346
through the years, obviously,

141
00:05:42.346 --> 00:05:44.796
this started taking on a greater and greater focus.

142
00:05:44.796 --> 00:05:47.081
What was the turning point for you,

143
00:05:47.081 --> 00:05:49.001
because you’re also an MD.

144
00:05:49.001 --> 00:05:53.087
<v ->Yeah, well, that was long before I was an MD.</v>

145
00:05:54.406 --> 00:05:57.174
The next big, sort of, revolution

146
00:05:57.174 --> 00:05:58.308
in my thinking about it,

147
00:05:58.308 --> 00:06:03.308
was, from 1969 to ‘72, I was Professor of Philosophy

148
00:06:04.282 --> 00:06:07.319
at East Carolina University,

149
00:06:07.319 --> 00:06:09.554
in Greenville, North Carolina.

150
00:06:09.554 --> 00:06:14.043
And, I began to hear this from my students.

151
00:06:15.043 --> 00:06:17.262
Plato has always been my favorite philosopher

152
00:06:17.262 --> 00:06:22.262
to teach, so when the students got to the point

153
00:06:22.934 --> 00:06:25.269
where Plato talks about the afterlife,

154
00:06:25.269 --> 00:06:26.738
they responded.

155
00:06:26.738 --> 00:06:28.506
So, over the next three years,

156
00:06:28.506 --> 00:06:30.708
I gathered about a dozen of these cases

157
00:06:30.708 --> 00:06:31.576
from my students.

158
00:06:31.576 --> 00:06:33.544
And then, as word spread,

159
00:06:33.544 --> 00:06:38.382
I was invited to various clubs around Greenville,

160
00:06:38.382 --> 00:06:42.353
and I just started collecting these things.

161
00:06:42.353 --> 00:06:44.389
So, when I went to medical school,

162
00:06:44.389 --> 00:06:46.358
in September of ‘72,

163
00:06:46.358 --> 00:06:49.294
I already had about a dozen cases of this.

164
00:06:49.294 --> 00:06:52.699
I mean, it’s a long, evolutionary process.

165
00:06:52.699 --> 00:06:56.367
Then, when I started medical school in '72,

166
00:06:56.367 --> 00:06:58.503
I had quite a number of professors

167
00:06:58.503 --> 00:07:00.072
who were very interested in this,

168
00:07:00.072 --> 00:07:02.741
and they would refer cases to me.

169
00:07:02.741 --> 00:07:05.009
So, I started talking about this

170
00:07:05.009 --> 00:07:08.964
at the medical college, in April of ‘73,

171
00:07:08.964 --> 00:07:10.348
during my first year.

172
00:07:10.348 --> 00:07:11.566
<v Regina>April ‘73.</v>

173
00:07:11.566 --> 00:07:12.850
<v ->Yes, so that was the first--</v>

174
00:07:12.850 --> 00:07:14.086
<v Regina>So, you’re almost, gosh,</v>

175
00:07:14.086 --> 00:07:16.321
40 years into it, now.

176
00:07:16.321 --> 00:07:18.439
<v ->Well, it depends on where you start, yeah, if you start--</v>

177
00:07:18.439 --> 00:07:20.341
<v Regina>Well, yeah, Plato '65.</v>

178
00:07:20.341 --> 00:07:21.588
<v Regina>Yeah, 50 years in '62.</v>

179
00:07:21.588 --> 00:07:23.010
<v ->It was '62, yeah, almost 50 years.</v>

180
00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:24.795
<v Regina>Almost 50 years into it.</v>

181
00:07:24.795 --> 00:07:26.031
So, that’s why they say,

182
00:07:26.031 --> 00:07:28.827
"You are the father of near death experience".

183
00:07:28.827 --> 00:07:29.666
<v ->Well, they say that.</v>

184
00:07:29.666 --> 00:07:31.502
<v Regina>Understanding, that’s the 'they'.</v>

185
00:07:31.502 --> 00:07:32.504
<v ->They say that, but to me, it's like</v>

186
00:07:32.504 --> 00:07:35.741
Plato and the ancient Greek philosophers.

187
00:07:35.741 --> 00:07:37.909
The ancient Greek philosophers

188
00:07:37.909 --> 00:07:38.810
were into this,

189
00:07:38.810 --> 00:07:41.579
and they called people like this,

190
00:07:41.579 --> 00:07:45.450
who were reputed to return from death,

191
00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:49.419
revenants, and this was a big aspect

192
00:07:49.419 --> 00:07:51.210
of ancient Greek philosophy.

193
00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:53.391
That’s how I got interested in it,

194
00:07:53.391 --> 00:07:54.925
because you can’t really understand

195
00:07:54.925 --> 00:07:57.094
the origins of Western thought,

196
00:07:57.094 --> 00:08:00.064
unless you understand about these

197
00:08:00.064 --> 00:08:01.667
early philosophers’ interest

198
00:08:01.667 --> 00:08:04.202
in this very phenomenon that, today,

199
00:08:04.202 --> 00:08:06.070
we call the near-death experience.

200
00:08:06.070 --> 00:08:07.539
<v Regina>Mhm.</v>

201
00:08:09.477 --> 00:08:10.976
<v Regina>When you started encountering</v>

202
00:08:10.976 --> 00:08:12.877
some of these people, early on,

203
00:08:12.877 --> 00:08:14.478
can you give us just a couple of examples,

204
00:08:14.478 --> 00:08:16.090
because we love hearing them.

205
00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:16.830
<v ->Yeah.</v>

206
00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:17.938
<v Regina>Of some of the stories</v>

207
00:08:17.938 --> 00:08:21.331
that just captured you, and gripped you so deeply,

208
00:08:21.331 --> 00:08:26.331
that there was no choice but to continue.

209
00:08:26.457 --> 00:08:29.493
<v ->Well, Dr. Ritchie looms large in that.</v>

210
00:08:29.493 --> 00:08:31.361
<v Regina>Can you share his experience?</v>

211
00:08:31.361 --> 00:08:35.633
<v ->Yes, basically, in December of 1943,</v>

212
00:08:35.633 --> 00:08:37.951
at Camp Barkeley, Texas,

213
00:08:37.951 --> 00:08:39.838
he was a recruit into the army,

214
00:08:39.838 --> 00:08:42.274
and during his basic training,

215
00:08:42.274 --> 00:08:44.943
he developed double lobar pneumonia,

216
00:08:44.943 --> 00:08:49.280
and was found, apparently, dead, in the ward,

217
00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.883
of double lombar pneumonia.

218
00:08:51.883 --> 00:08:53.851
The doctor came, pronounced him dead.

219
00:08:53.851 --> 00:08:55.086
About nine minutes later,

220
00:08:55.086 --> 00:08:59.790
the ward boy, that was the person he had ever known,

221
00:08:59.790 --> 00:09:01.459
of his age, who had died.

222
00:09:01.459 --> 00:09:03.127
He couldn't face this,

223
00:09:03.127 --> 00:09:06.564
So, he came and persuaded Dr. Francie,

224
00:09:06.564 --> 00:09:09.000
who was the ward physician,

225
00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.003
to inject adrenaline,

226
00:09:11.003 --> 00:09:13.104
directly into George's heart.

227
00:09:13.104 --> 00:09:14.972
And, George came back.

228
00:09:14.972 --> 00:09:16.274
But, in the interim,

229
00:09:16.274 --> 00:09:18.576
he said, suddenly, he came to,

230
00:09:18.576 --> 00:09:20.880
and found himself out of his body.

231
00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:22.514
Nobody could see him.

232
00:09:22.514 --> 00:09:23.948
Nobody could hear him.

233
00:09:23.948 --> 00:09:26.484
And, as this experience progressed,

234
00:09:26.484 --> 00:09:29.020
he said the light started getting better.

235
00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:30.388
He found himself surrounded

236
00:09:30.388 --> 00:09:33.824
by a sort of three-dimensional panorama

237
00:09:33.824 --> 00:09:36.194
of everything he had ever done,

238
00:09:36.194 --> 00:09:39.064
and in the presence of this profound being

239
00:09:39.064 --> 00:09:42.767
of complete compassion and love,

240
00:09:42.767 --> 00:09:46.604
and had quite a number of experiences with this.

241
00:09:46.604 --> 00:09:50.375
And then, it greatly shaped his practice of medicine.

242
00:09:50.375 --> 00:09:54.045
After this, he went on to become a physician.

243
00:09:54.045 --> 00:09:55.280
He was only 20 years old,

244
00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:57.381
at the time of his experience.

245
00:09:57.381 --> 00:10:00.117
And, I knew George for the rest of his life.

246
00:10:00.117 --> 00:10:02.453
He was, I can honestly say,

247
00:10:02.453 --> 00:10:05.323
at my age now of 66,

248
00:10:05.323 --> 00:10:08.527
that George Ritchie is the finest human being

249
00:10:08.527 --> 00:10:10.261
I ever have known.

250
00:10:10.261 --> 00:10:12.631
Oh, I met him when I was 19,

251
00:10:12.631 --> 00:10:15.232
but he totally changed my life.

252
00:10:15.232 --> 00:10:18.202
But, after that, I think, the next one

253
00:10:18.202 --> 00:10:23.202
that was a very significant event to me,

254
00:10:23.708 --> 00:10:28.212
was, some time in late '69, or early '70,

255
00:10:28.212 --> 00:10:32.083
I was a Professor of Psychiatry, at East Carolina.

256
00:10:32.083 --> 00:10:34.651
And, a young man, who had been severely injured

257
00:10:34.651 --> 00:10:36.621
in an accident, about a year ago,

258
00:10:36.621 --> 00:10:39.807
and had obvious scarring and everything,

259
00:10:40.957 --> 00:10:43.193
made his way up after class, one day,

260
00:10:43.193 --> 00:10:46.897
and asked me, "Why don't we talk about life after death,

